WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.800
Okay, thank you all for being here.

00:00:06.800 --> 00:00:09.480
So I'm just going to present a little bit about a package that I've been working on

00:00:09.480 --> 00:00:12.160
over the last couple months called live code.

00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:17.280
So I teach a lot of statistical programming classes to a variety of different student

00:00:17.280 --> 00:00:20.860
levels and one of the tools I've been adopting more and more in my teaching is this idea

00:00:20.860 --> 00:00:21.860
of live coding.

00:00:21.860 --> 00:00:25.120
And these are a couple quotes from some academic papers from the computer science literature

00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:26.760
about what is live coding.

00:00:26.760 --> 00:00:30.320
I think we all probably have a pretty good idea, but I think one of the key things at

00:00:30.320 --> 00:00:34.919
least coming at it from an educator's perspective is this idea of when we're teaching people

00:00:34.919 --> 00:00:39.119
to code, one of the things we want to do is show them the thought process.

00:00:39.119 --> 00:00:42.119
So we don't want to just show them finished code, we want to show the process of generating

00:00:42.119 --> 00:00:47.040
code and also talk about and narrate the thought process that goes into solving that kind of

00:00:47.040 --> 00:00:48.040
thing.

00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:51.279
And I think this is a really important powerful tool and I've been sort of using it more and

00:00:51.279 --> 00:00:53.320
more in my teaching.

00:00:53.320 --> 00:00:57.680
But this is sort of in conflict with another sort of big idea within pedagogy, which is

00:00:57.680 --> 00:01:00.040
this idea of active versus passive learning.

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:03.599
The general preference is we want our students to be doing active things, engaging things,

00:01:03.599 --> 00:01:06.680
doing stuff with their hands, that kind of idea.

00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:09.080
Live coding is sort of inherently passive.

00:01:09.080 --> 00:01:13.000
They're sitting there watching you code things and they're listening to what you talk about

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:16.720
and in the little bit where it tends to be active, it's active in not a great way.

00:01:16.720 --> 00:01:19.480
The students will sit there and they'll type the same code that you're typing, they're

00:01:19.480 --> 00:01:23.320
repeating that same effort, and then they're not listening to what you're saying, which

00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:26.320
is sort of the most valuable thing that's going on here.

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:29.680
So live code is sort of an effort that I'm trying to make to move some of this stuff

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:34.160
away from sort of just purely passive, absorbing that information into a more active learning

00:01:34.160 --> 00:01:37.400
kind of thing, and particularly leveraging RStudio in this interactive environment to

00:01:37.400 --> 00:01:41.320
get them playing around with code to explore it and learn it in that way.

00:01:41.320 --> 00:01:44.519
So this is a screen cast of the package.

00:01:44.519 --> 00:01:47.800
Reload it so it launches.

00:01:47.800 --> 00:01:49.519
So live code has a lot going on.

00:01:49.519 --> 00:01:51.000
Don't worry about the code right now.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:54.000
It's just running one function called serve file.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:58.160
What it's doing is it's looking at the file that I currently have open in RStudio, launching

00:01:58.160 --> 00:02:03.879
a server, making that available, and what it's doing in real time or close to real time

00:02:03.879 --> 00:02:09.160
is syncing the contents of that file in my RStudio session to a webpage that the students

00:02:09.160 --> 00:02:10.479
can go to and log in on.

00:02:10.479 --> 00:02:14.479
So if you see this sort of little banner thing in the blue picture up in the upper right-hand

00:02:14.479 --> 00:02:18.600
corner here, what we see is that we're saying, welcome to live code.

00:02:18.600 --> 00:02:23.639
We're serving example.r at and then a bit link that they can connect to.

00:02:23.639 --> 00:02:26.919
All of this went by a little quick, so I'll play it again and try to narrate a little

00:02:26.919 --> 00:02:27.919
bit.

00:02:27.919 --> 00:02:29.279
So we launched the server.

00:02:29.279 --> 00:02:35.479
It figures out from the context what it should be doing, figures out my local network environment,

00:02:35.479 --> 00:02:39.320
and I get this server running locally, but that link should now be accessible to other

00:02:39.320 --> 00:02:40.320
people.

00:02:40.320 --> 00:02:43.919
They can click on it, connect, and so here I'm just demonstrating it by two sessions

00:02:43.919 --> 00:02:46.440
that are running simultaneously, and the idea is I should be able to scale this up

00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:49.919
to 50 or 100 or even 200 students.

00:02:49.919 --> 00:02:55.039
Other things, we see that we get syntax highlighting, note as I make changes in the file in RStudio,

00:02:55.039 --> 00:02:59.919
that change is propagating over to the session in the web browser, and other sort of nice

00:02:59.919 --> 00:03:06.000
quality of life things like if we look at the line that's highlighted in the web server

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:11.119
is the same thing where my cursor is in the file in RStudio, so we're trying to sync all

00:03:11.119 --> 00:03:12.320
of this kind of stuff.

00:03:12.759 --> 00:03:15.639
There's a lot of things going on behind the scenes here, but this is really leveraging

00:03:15.639 --> 00:03:18.919
a lot of the powerful tools that RStudio has written for doing asynchronous programming,

00:03:18.919 --> 00:03:23.479
so if you heard Winston Chang's wonderful talk yesterday, we're doing all of that kind

00:03:23.479 --> 00:03:26.679
of stuff to make this sort of seamless, but the goal is to make this as accessible to

00:03:26.679 --> 00:03:28.600
educators as possible.

00:03:28.600 --> 00:03:31.720
To give you a little bit more of an idea about what's sort of going on behind the scenes,

00:03:31.720 --> 00:03:33.279
this is the main function.

00:03:33.279 --> 00:03:38.320
This is mainly the thing that you should interact with, so before I ran it without any arguments,

00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:42.399
but it's using things from the RStudio API to figure out, okay, what file do you have

00:03:42.399 --> 00:03:43.399
currently open?

00:03:43.399 --> 00:03:46.899
I had a file called example.r, so it's picking that out for me and doing it.

00:03:46.899 --> 00:03:50.960
Other things like specifying the IP address that you want the server to run on.

00:03:50.960 --> 00:03:53.679
Most people who are probably going to use this don't want to know about running a server,

00:03:53.679 --> 00:03:57.479
don't want to know about IP addresses or ports, so one of the things that the package tries

00:03:57.479 --> 00:04:03.000
to do is figure that out for you automatically, so here it's using this 10.port.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:06.320
If you know something about IP addresses, that's a private IP address, so this is actually

00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:09.080
from me running this on the hotel network here.

00:04:09.080 --> 00:04:11.759
That's not something that's accessible to the outside world.

00:04:11.759 --> 00:04:15.679
I can't do anything about that as a package maintainer, but I can at least give my users

00:04:15.679 --> 00:04:19.920
some information about that, saying, hey, you're on a private IP address, only other

00:04:19.920 --> 00:04:22.440
people who are on that same network will probably be able to access it.

00:04:22.440 --> 00:04:26.079
So again, trying to provide some feedback, tell you what's going on there.

00:04:26.079 --> 00:04:30.600
Autosave, so again, this is trying to do this in a sort of nice, elegant way, so we can

00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:37.320
leverage RStudio to save the files automatically and then only push things to our users when

00:04:37.320 --> 00:04:40.880
we actually make a change, so we're not constantly pushing the same file over and over again.

00:04:40.880 --> 00:04:41.880
We wait for a change.

00:04:41.880 --> 00:04:43.920
When that happens, it gets sent out to everybody.

00:04:43.920 --> 00:04:47.579
Otherwise we don't do things, and depending on how big the file is and how many people

00:04:47.579 --> 00:04:51.519
you have connected, we can set that interval in terms of when it pulls things to be slower

00:04:51.519 --> 00:04:55.959
or faster, so I can send changes out every two minutes, so on and so forth, and we're

00:04:55.959 --> 00:05:00.040
playing with other kind of cool things, like sending messages to your users, that kind

00:05:00.040 --> 00:05:05.559
of thing, and it's very early days for the package, but we'd like you to play with it,

00:05:05.559 --> 00:05:08.559
try to break it, try to stress test it, that kind of thing, and let us know how it goes.

00:05:08.559 --> 00:05:09.559
There you go.

00:05:09.559 --> 00:05:10.559
Thank you.

00:05:10.559 --> 00:05:10.559


